{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17470914","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17470914"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:42:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:42:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"73"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"73","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/73"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.04,0.04,0.71,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"73"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54547"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"73","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/73"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"73"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40056"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1254"},{"type":"tags","id":"2545"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"7949"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"927"},{"type":"contributions","id":"950"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41978"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44017"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54547","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54547"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn eight-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of sore throat and fever. His parent describes a rough-feeling rash that started on his trunk and gradually spread to his arms and legs. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.0\u00b0C. He has generalised lymphadenopathy. Examination of his oral mucosa reveals an erythematous tongue. There is an erythematous rash that feels fine and rough across his trunk, with lines also present in his armpits and elbow creases.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Roseola","Measles","Viral exanthem","Scarlet fever","Kawasaki disease"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation in this case is most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Escarlet fever\u003C/strong\u003E. This infection, caused by Group A Streptococcus, typically presents with pharyngitis, fever, and a characteristic rash. The rough \u0027sandpaper-like\u0027 rash involving the trunk and limbs, with sparing of the palms, soles, and face, is typical of scarlet fever. The erythematous tongue described is likely a \u0027strawberry tongue\u0027, which is another hallmark of this condition. The red lines in the skin creases (axilla and elbow creases) are likely Pastia\u0027s lines, which are also characteristic of scarlet fever.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKawasaki disease\u003C/strong\u003E is an important differential diagnosis to consider, but it is less likely in this case. Kawasaki disease typically affects children under five years of age, and the fever would usually persist for at least five days. Additional features such as non-exudative conjunctivitis, changes in the lips and oral mucosa, and extremity changes (e.g., erythema of palms and soles, or periungual desquamation) would be expected in Kawasaki disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERoseola\u003C/strong\u003E is typically seen in younger children, usually between 6 months and 3 years of age. It presents with a high fever for several days, followed by a rapid defervescence and the appearance of a maculopapular rash. The rash in roseola is usually not rough to the touch, and a strawberry tongue is not a feature of this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeasles\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with the triad of cough, coryza (runny nose), and conjunctivitis, along with fever and a maculopapular rash. The rash in measles usually starts on the face and behind the ears before spreading to the trunk and extremities. Koplik spots (white spots on the buccal mucosa) are pathognomonic for measles but are not described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EViral exanthem\u003C/strong\u003E is a broad term that can encompass various viral infections causing rash and fever. While it remains a possibility, the specific features described in this case (sandpaper-like rash, strawberry tongue, Pastia\u0027s lines) are more suggestive of scarlet fever than a non-specific viral exanthem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven the clinical presentation of pharyngitis, fever, sandpaper-like rash, strawberry tongue, and Pastia\u0027s lines, scarlet fever is the most likely diagnosis in this case. Prompt treatment with antibiotics is typically recommended to prevent complications and reduce transmission.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Scarlet fever is characterized by a sandpaper-like rash, strawberry tongue, and Pastia\u0027s lines in skin creases.","Scarlet fever is caused by Group A Streptococcus and commonly presents with pharyngitis and fever.","Differential diagnoses for fever and rash in children include Kawasaki disease, roseola, measles, and viral exanthems."],"references":["Basetti S, Hodgson J, Rawson TM, Majeed A. Scarlet fever: a guide for general practitioners. London J Prim Care (Abingdon). 2017 Aug 11;9(5):77-79. doi: 10.1080/17571472.2017.1365677. PMID: 29081840; PMCID: PMC5649319.","Ely JW, Seabury Stone M. The generalized rash: part I. Differential diagnosis. Am Fam Physician. 2010 Mar 15;81(6):726-34. PMID: 20229971."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40056"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"73"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40056"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-07T11:04:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-07T11:05:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"73"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54547"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relations